The information about changing flood risk and the performance of the sewer network will help inform TWUL's risk-based investment decisions, the submission of their future Asset Management Plans to Ofwat. It will also help them to be more informed when dealing with other external stakeholders with flood responsibilities such as the Environment Agency and Lead Local Flood Authorities in regard to pluvial, fluvial and groundwater flooding impacts particularly in relation to the resilience of its assets.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2015</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>300FBE00-48DB-4832-87F2-D09C4F84D81F</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Economic</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>56dd752ee38393.92959767</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>We coupled a regional groundwater model and an urban groundwater model to simulate the impact of extreme, high groundwater levels on Thames Water's sewer network in a Chalk catchment in southern England. We calculated historic and future groundwater flood risk using ensembles of past and future climate generated using climate model outputs and statistical weather generators. The return periods of groundwater flood events of different magnitude were calculated to reduce under future climate. This information is feeding into TWUL's strategic planning for the investment in, and management of, their sewer network.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The methodology is likely to be used across TWUL's catchments, providing them for the first time with an assessment of groundwater flood risk across their systems.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>C9A04EA8-790C-4FFF-A1F7-B5B7EE4ED626</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>56dd9801b7f779.49163981</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:pol